[2
Date: Wed, 18 Aug 1999 11:10:54 -0400
From: "Dority, Tom (CAP, GEFA)" <Tom.Dority@gecapital.com>
Subject: PRO/AH> Elephant blindness
I am a reader of the postings in ProMED and find great interest in the
topics covered.
I can only offer a suggestion that indicates a lack of vitamin A in the
diets of the elephants. I am not suggesting that the quantity of vitamin A
in the diet is low but, maybe, low protein intake or intake of too many
nitrates or preservatives is destroying the available vitamin A.
Hydrogenated oil such as coconut or palm oil could destroy the chance of
absorption of vitamin A. How often are food ingredients restocked (rancid)?
Have those ingredients changed? Does this restocking occur when symptoms
disappear or re-occur? For the imported animals -- has there exposure to
light increased directly or indirectly (highly reflective painted surfaces
or intensity of sun exposure) which would dramatically increase the need for
vitamin A?
---
Tom Dority
Tom.Dority@gecapital.com
USA
