[3
Date: Thu, 19 Aug 1999 12:31:22 +0700
From: Daniel Libraty <dlibraty@mozart.inet.co.th>

I would like to ask whether there is any temporal association between the
ivermectin given 4 times per year (I assume about every 3 months) and these
inflammatory ocular episodes every 3-4 months? Were they receiving
ivermectin prior to their transfer to Jerusalem? If there is an
association, one hypothesis might be that these elephants have a chronic
microfilaremia (if elephants can get filarial disease -- one with ocular
tropism like onchocerciasis in humans?) and that partial treatment with the
ivermectin leads to an antigen flare and subsequent inflammatory bilateral
eye disease (not clear to me whether all recurrent episodes are a
keratoconjunctivitis or also have an anterior uveitis component?). Given the
periodicity of a variety of human filarial diseases, a routine blood smear
for parasites might not be a sensitive way of detecting such an
infection.
---
Daniel H. Libraty, M.D.
Assistant Professor of Medicine
University of Massachusetts School of Medicine
USAMC-AFRIMS, Department of Virology
Bangkok, Thailand
***
[4
Date: Wed, 18 Aug 1999 15:52:24 -0600 (MDT)
From: Christa Bruns <cbruns@cvmbs.colostate.edu>

Another thought would be Malignant Catarrhal Fever (MCF), particularly if
the animals had any contact with wildebeest or sheep. There is an a good
PCR (polymerase chain reaction) test (whole blood) for both SA-MCF (Sheep
Associated Malignant Catarrhal Fever) and WD-MCF (Wildebeest Derived
Malignant Catarrhal Fever). This disease does cause corneal opacity and
probably should be ruled out.
---
Christa Bruns
cbruns@cvmbs.colostate.edu
